<p>
  Nothing has changed. Not the surgery, the odds, or the outcome. Only the
  wording. Yet people often make different decisions depending on which
  version they hear.
</p>
<p>
  The first description draws attention to survival. The second puts death at
  the center. One comforts; the other alarms. This is the framing effect: our
  response to information is shaped not only by the facts, but by how those
  facts are presented.
</p>
<p>
  Psychologists Daniel Kahneman and Amos Tversky demonstrated this effect in
  their 1981 research on decision-making. Their work revealed an uncomfortable
  truth: we do not judge information in a vacuum. Wording, context, and
  emphasis influence what we notice, how we feel, and ultimately what we
  choose.
</p>
<p>
  Advertisers understand this well. &ldquo;95% fat-free&rdquo; sounds better
  than &ldquo;contains 5% fat.&rdquo; &ldquo;Save $50&rdquo; feels more
  appealing than &ldquo;avoid paying $50 extra.&rdquo; The numbers are
  identical. The emotional response is not.
</p>
<p>
  We like to believe facts speak for themselves. But facts usually arrive
  inside a frame, and whoever chooses the frame can influence the choice. To
  think clearly, look at the same fact from both sides before deciding.
</p>

